\details{
\subsection{G-computation (\code{method = "gcomp"})}{

Fits E[Y | A, L] using \code{glm()} (or \code{mgcv::gam()} if the formula
contains \code{s()} or \code{te()} terms). \code{\link[=contrast]{contrast()}} standardises over the
target population (controlled by \code{estimand}) to obtain E[Y^a] under each
intervention. For \code{"gcomp"}, the estimand can be overridden in
\code{\link[=contrast]{contrast()}} — fit once, contrast with multiple estimands.

For longitudinal data, uses ICE g-computation (Zivich et al., 2024):
outcome models are fitted one per time point via backward iteration,
conditioning on baseline confounders (\code{confounders}), time-varying
confounders (\code{confounders_tv}), and their lags up to \code{history} steps.
}

\subsection{IPW (\code{method = "ipw"})}{

Calls \code{WeightIt::weightit()} to estimate propensity-score-based weights
for the desired \code{estimand}, then fits a weighted outcome model via
\code{WeightIt::glm_weightit()}. The estimand is fixed at fitting time.
Supports binary, categorical, and continuous treatments (anything
\code{WeightIt} supports). Only \code{static()} interventions are supported
in \code{\link[=contrast]{contrast()}}, because the weights were estimated under the observed
treatment distribution.

For longitudinal data, calls \code{WeightIt::weightitMSM()}. The denominator
model at each time \code{k} includes baseline confounders, concurrent
time-varying confounders, and lagged treatment. The numerator model
includes only baseline confounders and lagged treatment (standard
stabilized weights), unless overridden via \code{numerator}.
}

\subsection{Matching (\code{method = "matching"})}{

Calls \code{MatchIt::matchit()} to create matched sets. The estimand is
fixed at fitting time. Only \code{static()} interventions are supported
in \code{\link[=contrast]{contrast()}}.
}

\subsection{Estimands}{\tabular{lll}{
   Estimand \tab Population averaged over \tab Applicability \cr
   \code{"ATE"} \tab All individuals \tab Always \cr
   \code{"ATT"} \tab Observed treated (\code{A = 1}) \tab Binary point treatment only \cr
   \code{"ATC"} \tab Observed controls (\code{A = 0}) \tab Binary point treatment only \cr
}


For continuous, categorical, multivariate, or longitudinal treatments,
use \code{estimand = "ATE"} and pass a \code{subset} expression to \code{\link[=contrast]{contrast()}}
for subgroup effects.
}

\subsection{Identifiability assumptions}{

All methods assume: (1) exchangeability (no unmeasured confounding given
L), (2) positivity (every individual has positive probability of each
treatment value given L), (3) consistency (the observed outcome under the
observed treatment equals the potential outcome). Positivity is checked
automatically and a warning is issued if near-violations are detected.
}
